title: For Sale:  John Wayne Commemorative
postcontent:
I am selling a Colt "American Remembers" John Wayne special edition and a Winchester lever action "American Remembers" John Wayne special edition.   Both guns are in excellent condition with no scratches, blemishes or nicks.  In addition, both are unfired.


A little information about the pistol:

Only 3,500 John Wayne Tribute .45 Pistols have been authorized for this  edition.  The John Wayne Tribute .45 Pistol is a working, semi-automatic pistol with the solid performing power counted on by all those who relied on this trusted sidearm during their service to our country. The Colt .45 was a favorite of John Wayne and was featured frequently in his military films. This pistol is polished and decorated by craftsmen commissioned specifically by America Remembers with artwork we have created specifically for this military Tribute.

The slide is polished and decorated in elegant 24-karat gold and nickel with a blued background. The artwork includes classic images of John Wayne, and inspirational words of encouragement from the Duke, featured along with patriotic American symbols, which meant so much to this legendary icon and continue to represent the proud and patriotic spirit of the American people.

The left slide features the central portrait of John Wayne in the role of a Marine Officer. To the left is his quote, “Courage is Being Scared to Death…But Saddling Up Anyway” scrolled beside our trusted national symbol of strength, the American bald eagle. 

To the right is his quote, “A Man’s Got to Do…What a Man’s Got to Do” and the eagle, globe and anchor logo of the Marines. At the muzzle end, “Duke,” John Wayne’s celebrated nickname, is featured.

The right side of the slide features the central portrait of John Wayne in the role of a Naval Officer. To the left, it reads “Talk Low… Talk Slow and Don’t Talk too Much!” scrolled proudly beside the familiar American symbols of the Liberty Bell and the US Navy Anchor symbol. To the right, it reads “The American Flag…The Best Flag God Gave to Any Country,” scrolled in front of a waving Stars and Stripes. At the muzzle end, John Wayne’s signature is faithfully displayed.





A little about the rifle:

Only 3,500 John Wayne Tribute Rifles have been authorized for this edition and demand is expected to be very strong for these commemorative firearms.  Every metal surface of this John Wayne commemorative rifle is finished in a mirror-polished, lustrous deep blue. Craftsmen commissioned by America Remembers decorate each of these commemorative firearms. The receiver features artwork in 24-karat gold and scrollwork in the  tradition of the finest presentation firearms. 

The left side of the barrel features John Wayne’s signature, and inset into the stock is a 24-karat gold-plated medallion with John Wayne’s portrait. The handsome walnut stocks are checkered on this John Wayne commemorative rifle and finished to a high gloss, and the hammer and trigger are polished and decorated in 24-karat gold.

The right side of this John Wayne rifle, the receiver features a scene familiar to every fan of Western classics. In it, John Wayne leads the U.S. Cavalry through the buttes and dry gullies of desolate Monument Valley. Above the scene flies a banner that reads “John Wayne.”

The left side of the receiver features John Wayne as a wagon train scout, leading settlers and a cavalry escort through Apache territory. If you look closely on this John Wayne commemorative rifle, you will see a rifle in John Wayne’s right hand! Handsome scrollwork in the tradition of the finest firearms frames the artwork, with all artwork being featured in stunning 24-karat gold on these commemorative firearms.

postcontent: If your looking for an Ideal carry 9mm, then the Walther P5 compact is the weapon for you. It's the 9mm big brother to Walther's PPK. It's even been used in several Bond films with Sean Connery and Roger Moore. No longer made,  the P5 was brought into the US in the 80's. This one was from 1986. It's the perfect size for carry but remains extremely accurate. It packs a powerful punch a 9 x 19 full size 9mm should. It has some great German features that put the battery release to use as a decocker. It ejects to left. The magazine release has been brought up on the grip in the P5 compact version, I like that better than it's predessors and other European pistols with the release on the heel. This is truly a rare gun. It has the coolness of a ppk, but it's a full 9mm. It comes with the hard to find custom holster, the original box and manual and 2-7 round clips. I Look forward to hearing from you. Shoot safe, shoot straight and shoot often...

title: For Sale/Trade:  Collectors grade Norinco SKS
postcontent:
Looking to trade or sell for enough for a pistol. It's been appraised up to $1200. I just don't shoot it. So looking for something I will shoot. Have around 400 rounds of ammo I can add for right trade. I'm valuing it at between $6-800. 

All matching Norinco Chinese sks. Sporter version. As can be seen in pic your typical sporter sks had a shortened barrel, bayonet lug removed, thumbhole stock and adapted to accept ak mags which redesigned the bolt carrier with no stripper clip slots. The sporter I am selling has a non thumbhole stock and does not accept ak mags.  Is full size barrel with bayonet and does use stripper clips for loading. It's 100% matching, original and real. Have green sling, cleaning kit that fits in stock, screwdriver type bayonet.  I have owned for over 22 years. Less than 500 rounds shot thru it. Well taken care of and pristine condition. Again all numbers match. Is stamped Tucson AZ. Is also a legit DB stamp. Here's the history:

In 1989 sks were stamped sporter or sks-m to be allowed for import after a 1989 ban. These rifles were fitted with Monte Carlo or thumbhole stocks. Also made and adapted to accept ak mags. Also had the bayo lug removed. The rifle I have has had none of the cosmetic changes yet is stamped sporter. Plus it has the DB stamp. That means deport Bangladesh. Some Chinese made sks were stamped this or DP(Pakistan) or DK(Kampuchea). DP typically adds 10% value. DK about 15-20%. And the most rare DB adding up to 50% based on condition. Many DP have been forged to appear DB. They are easy to tell due to the mis proportion of the humps of the B. so the sporter mis-stamp, DB stamp and #'s matching drives it to a collectors rifle. 
And when I mention the 1989 ban I don't mean the 1994 awb. 
Also another change was the bolt carrier was changed on sporters with no slots for striped clips since they used ak removable mags and no stripper clip was needed. 
Most sporters had barrels shortened too.
